ELF = linux executable

Case sensitivity is IMPORTANT in linux.
"Linux is a ruthless bitch."
		- Gunny Gerwing

Get back to home directory:
	cd
	cd ~
	cd $HOME
	mkdir - p			:		-p option switch forces creation 
Switch between last two directory paths easier:
	cd -
	
Perfrom as root:

	sudo !!
	
	
	
	
{} \; 		-> means to take the input {} and the \; specifies to stop the exec. SUPER IMPORTANT!!!!!!!
	
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
FILE MANIPULATION COMMANDS:


curl cht.sh/<command>			:			provides an example syntax for command
	
	^^ 'curl for the gurls'



touch	:	creates files, manipulates timestamps	
mkdir	:	creates a directory
rm		:	remove a file
rmdir	:	remove a file
rm -rf	:	removes recursively and forcefully
ls		:	lists contents of a directory
ls -a	:	lists all (including hidden files, prefixed by a '.')
pwd		:	print working directory
cp		:	copies files
mv		:	moves or renames files
less	:	prints output to screen in small chunks that can be paged through.		has /	pattern search functionality
more	:	prints output to screen in one large chunk
ln	:	creates symbolic links
file	:	returns file type (


---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
BASIC UNIX COMMANDS

	** FIND COMMANDS **
	
		locate	:	locates files by name				#make sure you include a 'sudo updatedb' to update the database after using locate
		find	:	searches for files in a directory hierarchy
			find PATH [OPTIONS]
			
			find . [OPTIONS] 		(find within present working directory)
			find / [OPTIONS]		(find starting at root of file system)
		 	find -name		(denotes case-sensitive file)
 			find -iname 		(denotes case-insensitive file)

		
			
			
		grep	:	locates STRINGS within files
			grep (basic)
			grep -E or egrep
			grep -P
			ps -elf | egrep -B1 "ssh"
					-A (after)
					-C (before and after)
				would search for instances of string "ssh" in ps -elf and also the context of the line before it(B1 = before, 1 line)
			
			egrep "PATTERN" filename
			egrep "PATTERN|OTHERPATTERN" (uses a logical 'or)
			
			
			
			
			
		which	:	shows where a command is stored
		whereis	:	shows where a command is stored (with man page location)
		whatis	:	provides synopsis of man page






------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Symbolic Links

Soft links are more like desktop shortcuts in windows.

Hard links are like real copies of files that point to the same locations in memory. 



    
    
    










